{"identifier":{"interfaceLanguage":"swift","url":"doc:\/\/OpenSwiftUI\/documentation\/OpenSwiftUI\/ProposedViewSize"},"primaryContentSections":[{"declarations":[{"platforms":["macOS"],"languages":["swift"],"tokens":[{"text":"@frozen","kind":"attribute"},{"text":" ","kind":"text"},{"text":"struct","kind":"keyword"},{"text":" ","kind":"text"},{"text":"ProposedViewSize","kind":"identifier"}]}],"kind":"declarations"},{"content":[{"anchor":"overview","type":"heading","text":"Overview","level":2},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"During layout in OpenSwiftUI, views choose their own size, but they do that"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"in response to a size proposal from their parent view. When you create"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"a custom layout using the "},{"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/OpenSwiftUI\/documentation\/OpenSwiftUI\/Layout","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":" protocol, your layout container"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"participates in this process using "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"ProposedViewSize"},{"type":"text","text":" instances."},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"The layout protocol’s methods take a proposed size input that you"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"can take into account when arranging views and calculating the size of"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"the composite container. Similarly, your layout proposes a size to each"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"of its own subviews when it measures and places them."}],"type":"paragraph"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Layout containers typically measure their subviews by proposing several"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"sizes and looking at the responses. The container can use this information"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"to decide how to allocate space among its subviews. A"},{"typ